post_title: THE BIG FINALE (Dispatch 7 & 8)
author: @shosho089
text:
The thing is, if you really pay attention, the twist with Visi isn't really that surprising. She joined the Z-Team with the point of "no questions asked," she looked uncomfortable when Robert spoke about trust after his Mecha Man reveal,  the comment about "old friends" when she was at the warehouse, her line about "we all pay for who we were in the past," etc.  It all lined up to her working for Shroud at some point. 

Did I hope I was wrong because I love the plucky ones? Yes. Was I surprised? Not really. But I AM glad that she came clean and Robert didn't find out through Shroud. I'm ALSO super glad BB wasn't a twist villain and is genuinely a good person who just makes some questionable choices, because she's a cutie patootie. Expectation subversion in the best way possible!

post_title: SÃ∂iÃ∂lÃ∂kÃ∂sÃ∂oÃ∂nÃ∂gÃ∂ NakeyJakey is Outdated
author: @noblepeaceprize8913
text:
Jakey, I want to tell you a bit of a story

This year I have listened to 52 albums, one for each week in the year. And during this year, I've realized that the best way to consume any kind of art is comparable to how to healthily go through a relationship. Every relationship has its flaws. If you focus on these flaws, the relationship will most certainly fail. But if you take those same flaws in stride, you will realize that those same flaws can become more reasons to love someone.

This also applies to all kinds of art. For example, my favorite album this year (and maybe of all time) has a lot of problems. The lyrics sometimes feel obtuse, sometimes the vocals don't sync with the instrumentals, and it's an album that is hard to recommend to someone who doesn't listen to that particular sound.

But that album also has a sound that I have been looking for for years. It tells a story that connects with me so much, that after my first listen, I cried so hard that i hallucinated. It is one of the only albums that I will go back and listen to, front to back.

That album is ROMCOM.

I would like ROMCOM less if it was "flawless". Its flaws is why I continue to think it's a 10/10, even if it's not a "perfect" album.

That's also applies to your channel. I, personally, wouldn't watch your content if it was "flawless". What some see as flaws, others see as relatability.

Please keep being "flawed". Please keep making "flawed" art. Please keep being "outdated". What is outdated to some, is familiar to others

Keep up the good work :)!

post_title: Leaving the Mormon Church
author: @SkylerDragon
text:
Hi. This helped me so much. I‚Äôm young, not terribly young. And I am in the church. Still. Only issue? The rest of my family believe. And I cannot seem to. They had their ups and downs, yes, but I cannot seem to believe. And it hurts because my mother makes me feel wrong for it. Yes, my friends in church understand and care so much. But my mother? She barely survived my (still somewhat religious) sibling coming out as trans masc. She makes me feel wrong for it. And it hurts. I have poor mental health and what has been happening to me has made my depression worse. I don‚Äôt hate the church. Heck, the Book of Mormon is historically accurate, you cannot say that was not written then. But it‚Äôs hard to make my mother happy and my autism makes everything so much harder.

But hearing you talk about your good experience, finding that some people will be amazing if I leave and others not so much, it helped. So much. Thank you for sharing this. I had a particularly bad day today but when I watched this? My notes app wasn‚Äôt attacked with my vents and need to peel off my skin XD 

So thank you.

post_title: Leaving the Mormon Church
author: @haydensmith2465
text:
Parker, you had me crying alongside you. Your story is mine. I‚Äôm 24, I grew up in Utah, and my mom left the church when I was 10, which prompted my parents‚Äô divorce, (amongst other things). I held so firmly to the values that the church gave me, but I struggled with the doctrine.

For my whole life, everyone had such high expectations for me. My mom even told me that out of all her kids, she believed that I‚Äôd be most likely to stay in the church. Between my family and friends, I felt like I had to‚Ä¶ But that whole time, I was struggling with my sexuality, and the prospect of never having the promised blessings I grew up with. It broke me‚Ä¶

Regardless, I went to seminary and I took missionary-prep classes as my anxiety worsened. When I got diagnosed with Crohn‚Äôs Disease at 17, I used that as an excuse to not serve, and I stopped attending church shortly after.

I cried hearing you talk about this because I remembered how lonely I felt when I stopped going. I felt ostracized when everyone was preparing for missions, or enrolling at BYU. Everyone at school knew me as a Mormon guy with high standards, and I hated having that identity because I didn‚Äôt want that for my future. So many of my friends were disappointed to discover that I stopped attending church.

That said, I found so much comfort in hearing you share your experiences. I‚Äôve followed you on YouTube for at least two years now, and I fully believed you were LDS. Thank you for taking the time to be a good person, and inspiring me to have confidence in where my values are. I‚Äôm not as confident or as content as you are, but I‚Äôm on the right path with going to the gym more frequently, spending more time with my parents, learning to cook healthier meals, etc., and in the span of a few minutes you‚Äôve helped me to conceptualize the impact of years of religious trauma. That understanding is worth more than I can state. Regardless, thank you Parker üôåüèª

post_title: Leaving the Mormon Church

text:
Hi, 20 years mormon here. Been miserable my whole life. Left at 21 after a suicide attempt for the anxiety my strict mormon parents gave me. 

I'll always say leaving the church is the best choice to make, but what's important is what makes you comfortable. 

Never been happier, but also I still struggle a lot by my family and community not accepting who I am as a person, but I found a family in all my friends and acquaintances I've made through my years outside the church

post_title: How Dollar General Is Secretly Robbing Its Customers
author: @lakithunder4569
text:
This doesn't even touch on the Dollar General's actual business model which is way more evil than just deceptive pricing. They open stores right next to local grocery stores then run them out of business by undercutting them on their most profitable products. They can do this because they're big enough to get special deals with suppliers, and They can run stores at a loss until they beat out the competition, then raise prices.
Often these local grocers are the only place to get groceries for miles, so when Dollar General runs them out of business, communities are left without anywhere to get fresh produce. Yes this is an intentional business model. The only solution is to get them out of your town.

post_title: How Dollar General Is Secretly Robbing Its Customers
author: @memesthednaofthesoul.
text:
Hey former DG worker here, 100% true. Worked there for 2 years and saw this happen all the time. Way shelf pricing works for them when I worked there was whenever corporate decided like they felt like actually updating the pricing, they would send the paper strips that go in the plastic shelf clip. Most of the time we could just get the sale stickers with the updated pricing and the "sale" we were running but once the "sales" were done we'd take it off and the self price would show. Got to the point we would use sticker guns to mark individual items with their actual prices when it was slow.

What I was told to do when the pricing didn't match was to apologize and ask if they still wanted it. We tried to change it where we could but some items didnt allow us to price change (usually holiday, cosmetics, and meds).

If you can, shop local or somewhere else. If you can't, PLEASE check best by dates and try to avoid refrigerated items. They never tought people to rotate items so out of date items would stay up on shelfs for a really long time and the fridges were never at the correct temps.

author: @8181mathew
text: When I was a kid, one of the local bus drivers lived just down the road from me out in the woods. She had a buck she took in after he was rescued named ‚ÄúBucky‚Äù and he would jump around and play like an excited dog. It was a quiet area that didn‚Äôt ever have much going on so my parents would let me take my dirt bike down to the old oil well road right by her house. I stopped and visited with them often and would help her out if she ever needed. Mostly just helping haul all the food around to feed the animals or splitting firewood for the winter. Got to spend a lot of time with Bucky over the 2 years he was alive. There were some dumpsters just off the road between her house and my parents. One day I was hauling the trash off and his head and neck was strung up on the barbed wire fence right by the dumpsters where she would obviously see it with his distinctive and extremely visible hunter‚Äôs orange collar still around his neck. Broke my heart. Broke it even more seeing how hurt she was when she found out. I made a small pine box and buried him out on her land. Some people are just full of pure evil. We never found out who did it. Being the bus driver that would take all the kids to the 4H camps and events, she was well loved by the most all of the town. Whatever slimy bastard did it kept quiet about it. Probably knew what would happen.

author: @ClonetrooperCaptain

post_title: Ocean Spray Responds To Videos Of Cranberry Cans Filled With Water
author: @wolfjamesgames
text: I currently work at the Kenosha Ocean Spray plant that produces sauce. Specifically on the sauce line. Don't listen to the "Only explanation" guy. Kenosha is the sole provider of all Ocean Spray sauce. It has been that way for over 50 years. I work in maintenance so I don't have clear answers either, but here's what I can tell you. These cans were purposefully filled with water during test runs. We do this in order to simulate full cans at weight for downstream commissioning. This involves labeling, casing, and palletizing the cases of cans. I can only imagine a mix up happened in shipping, and a pallet of test cans went out on a truck. Very unfortunate and defeating to have happened, but I am more glad at least everyone has stayed safe for the holiday and that the families got taken care of.

text: My old weenie dog had a similar morning routine lol. Always drank his water first, then took the longest potty break of the day. He refused to go on pads. So I carried him outside and sat him in his favorite spot to go. He would then scratch up the grass, bark three times and turn his body towards the house to signal he was done and ready to return to his bed. Which was my bed but he basically left me hanging on the edge while he slept at a diagonal angle, under the covers and head on the pillows. He was such a sweet old man. I lost him in June this year and miss him terribly.

post_title: I guess they are going to ruin everything
author: @JayneDoeAFK
text: Worse, in the UK, our government is *all in* on it. We're already using AI for everything, and our government brags about it frequently. They're looking into giving the biggest companies a 90% discount on energy, which they're claiming is to help our steelworks industry (which is owned by China by now anyway, so...huh?) but it's for all the surveillance related data centres we're selling off land to, to tech companies. We're screwed. So screwed. 90% energy discount for the energy sucking surveillance tech vampires, and we'll be footing the bill for our own oppression. Tax is going to increase like crazy, as will our energy bills, to make up for the discounts given to big tech. Idk why they don't just send out the black mirror robo dogs on us all now, and just be done with it.
